The following table is a historical summary
of the  Reserve Bank  of  India â€™s monetary policy decisions.  The central bank targets the reverse repurchase rate (Rev. Repo),
and repurchase rate (Repo) as one of the policy tools to set borrowing
costs in the economy. It also adjusts liquidity in the banking system
by changing the  cash reserve ratio  (CRR).  Since Bloomberg started surveys for the  Reserve Bank of India  in
April 2005, there have been a total of 79 scheduled rate decisions by
the bank of which 21 were unexpected, resulting in the survey matching
the actual rate decision 73% of the time.  Note: * Expected is when Bloomberg News survey median is equal to the announced  rate. Unexpected is when median is higher or lower than actual.  ^ Effective dates of cash reserve ratio changes may differ from the  annoucement dates.  To contact the reporter on this story:
